\p
\v 6 When \add ≈they'd all\add* come back after killing¦134606 the Philistine¦134609, the women¦134611 from the Israeli cities¦134614 had come out to meet King Sha'ul with singing¦134616 and dancing¦134618—playing tambourines¦134622 and \add ≈other instruments¦134624 with great happiness\add*.
\v 7 \add ≈However\add*, as they danced¦134628 they sang,\x + \xo 18:7: \xt 1Sam 21:11; 29:5.\x*
\q1 “Sha'ul has \add ≈killed\add* his thousands,
\q1 ≈and David his tens of thousands.”
\m
\v 8 Sha'ul \add ≈found that offensive and it made him very angry\add*. “They've attributed tens of thousands to David,” he \add ≈complained\add*, “but \add only\add* thousands to me. \add ≈Next thing he'll end up as king\add*.”
\v 9 \add ≈So¦134656\add* from that day¦134663 onwards, Sha'ul \add ≈remained wary of David and¦134665 kept an eye on him\add*.
\rem /s1 Saul Tries to Kill David
\p
\v 10 Then the next day, an evil spirit¦134671 from God¦134672 rushed¦134670 on Sha'ul and \add even\add* in the middle¦134680 of the house¦134682 he \add started\add* prophesying. As David was playing¦134684 near him (as he did every day), Sha'ul was holding a spear¦134689
\v 11 and he \add suddenly\add* hurled¦134694 \add *it\add*, saying, “I'll \add ≈pin that David to\add* the wall.” \add ≈But¦134694\add* twice when he did that, David \add ≈managed to elude¦134703 him\add*.
\p
\v 12 \add ≈So¦134708\add* Sha'ul \add ended up\add* afraid¦134708 of David because Yahweh was with him, but \add ≈was no longer with the king\add*.
\v 13 Then¦134721 Sha'ul¦134722 sent him \add ≈out of the room\add* and appointed him as the commander¦134726 of a thousand¦134728 warriors, \add ≈so\add* he came¦134730 and went¦134729 in front¦134731 of the people.\f + \fr 18:13 \ft It's not entirely clear what the implications of this coming and going were (and similarly at the end of v16). It could easily refer to him returning successfully from military excursions.\f*
\v 14 Yahweh was with David and he was succeeding¦134741 in \add ≈everything he did\add*.
\v 15 Sha'ul¦134746 \add ≈knew about his successes¦134750 and¦134752 couldn't stand looking at him¦134753\add*,
\v 16 \add ≈but all the people of\add* Israel and Yehudah loved David because \add ≈they observed his comings and goings¦134766\add*.
\s1 David wins Mikal as his wife
\rem /s1 David Marries Michal; David Marries Saul's Daughter
\p
\v 17 \add One day\add* Sha'ul told David, “Look, \add here's\add* my oldest daughter¦134777 Merab—I'll give¦134781 her to you for a wife. \add The only condition is that you\add* \add ≈become¦134786 a powerful warrior\add* for me and fight¦134792 Yahweh's battles¦134793.” (Sha'ul had said \add to himself\add*, “\add ≈I don't¦134797 need to hurt him physically—I'll let the Philistines¦134807 do that\add* \add for me\add*.”
\v 18 “Who am I,” David \add ≈asked\add*, “and who are my relatives in my father's¦134820 clan in Israel, that I should become the king's son-in-law?”
\p
\v 19 \add ≈However,\add* when it was the time¦134829 for Sha'ul to give his daughter¦134834 Merab to David, she was given¦134839 to Adriel the Meholathite \add ≈to marry\add*.
\p
\v 20 \add ≈Now\add* Sha'ul's \add other\add* daughter¦134846 Mikal loved¦134844 David, and \add when\add* they told \add *the king\add*, \add ≈he was pleased¦134854 about it\add*,
\v 21 \add ≈saying\add* \add to himself\add*, “I'll give¦134860 her to him \add ≈so\add* she can become a trap for him \add ≈so\add* the Philistines¦134871 \add ≈could be the ones to attack\add* him.” \add ≈So¦134858\add* he said a second¦134877 time, “You'll become a son-in-law of mine today.”
\v 22 Then¦134882 Sha'ul commanded¦134882 his servants, “Tell David privately¦134892, ‘Listen, the king is pleased with you, and all of us his servants love you. \add ≈So¦134882\add* now \add we think that you should\add* become the king's¦134904 son-in-law.’ ”
\p
\v 23 \add ≈So¦134906\add* they¦134906 told David privately¦134909, \add ≈but\add* \add *he\add* \add ≈responded\add*, “\add ≈Something that significant isn't likely to happen\add*. I'm \add ≈hard up\add* and \add ≈without much honour\add*.”
\p
\v 24 \add ≈When\add* Sha'ul's servants¦134928 told him what David had said,
\v 25 he \add ≈replied\add*, “\add ≈Pass this onto\add* David, ‘The king \add ≈doesn't want an expensive\add* bride¦134948 price—only a hundred¦134950 Philistine foreskins¦134951 taken from the king's enemies¦134954.’ ” \add ≈But\add* Sha'ul was \add still wanting\add* the Philistines¦134952 \add to be the ones\add* \add ≈to kill\add* David.
\v 26 \add ≈Now when\add* David \add ≈heard this from\add* the servants¦134967, \add ≈he decided that he could indeed marry the king's¦134978 daughter within the time period that had been given\add*,
\v 27 \add ≈so\add* he and his men \add ≈got ready\add* and went and \add ≈killed¦134989\add* \em two\em* hundred¦134991 Philistine men. He brought¦134993 them to the king¦134999 and \add ≈had them counted to fulfill the pledge\add*, and so Sha'ul \add had to\add* give his daughter¦135009 Mikal to become¦135000 his wife.
\p
\v 28 \add ≈But when\add* Sha'ul \add ≈realised\add* that Yahweh was \add ≈helping\add* David, and that his daughter¦135022 loved¦135025 him¦135025,
\v 29 \add ≈he became more\add* afraid¦135029 of David, \add ≈so he remained hostile\add* to David \add ≈from then on\add*.
\p
\v 30 \add ≈Whenever\add* the Philistine commanders \add ≈decided to attack\add*, David was more successful¦135051 than \add ≈any other of Sha'ul's commanders, so he became very famous\add*.
\c 19
\s1 Sha'ul persecutes David
\rem /s1 Saul Tries to Kill David; Jonathan Intercedes for David; David Is Persecuted by Saul
\p
\v 1 Then Sha'ul \add ≈urged\add* his son Yonatan and all his servants¦135071 to \add ≈kill¦135072\add* David, \add ≈but\add* Yonatan \add ≈really liked\add* David
\v 2 and told \add *him\add*, “My father¦135090 Sha'ul \add ≈wants to get rid of you¦135091, so please¦135095 watch out\add* in the morning¦135096. \add ≈Find a hiding place¦135098 and stay¦135097 there\add*.
\v 3 And \add ≈what I'll do\add*, I'll go out and stand¦135103 by my father in the countryside¦135107 where¦135108 you're \add hiding\add*, and I'll \add ≈bring you into the conversation to see what he'll say about you\add*.”
\p
\v 4 \add ≈So\add* \add the next morning,\add* Yonatan spoke¦135123 well of David to his father¦135130 Sha'ul, saying, “Don't let the king¦135136 sin¦135135 against his servant¦135137, against David, because¦135143 he hasn't sinned¦135141 against you, and actually, \add ≈he's been a big help\add* to you.
\v 5 He \add ≈took his life¦135153 into his hands when he fought against\add* \add @Goliat\add*, and Yahweh \add ≈used it to save\add* all Israel. \add ≈So¦135150\add* why would you sin¦135169 against innocent¦135171 blood¦135170 by putting David to death \add ≈for no reason\add*.”
\p
\v 6 Sha'ul listened¦135178 to Yonatan, then \add *he\add* promised, “As surely as Yahweh lives, he won't be put to death¦135189.”
\v 7 \add Afterwards,\add* Yonatan called¦135191 David and told him \add ≈what had been said\add*. Then¦135191 he brought¦135203 David back \add to work for\add* Sha'ul and \add ≈things carried on as before\add*.
\rem /s1 Michal Helps David Escape from Saul
\p
\v 8 Then war \add ≈broke out\add* again, and David went¦135220 out and battled against the Philistines¦135223 and defeated¦135224 them \add ≈so badly that\add* they fled away from \add ≈him¦135229\add*.
\p
\v 9 \add One day\add* as Sha'ul was sitting¦135241 in his house¦135240, an evil spirit¦135232 from Yahweh \add ≈came on him\add*. He had his spear¦135242 in his hand, and David was playing¦135245 \add the harp\add*.
\v 10 Sha'ul tried to hit David with the spear, but David eluded¦135254 him and the spear went into the wall. Then¦135248 David slipped away and fled that night¦135265.
\rem /s1 Michal Saves David's Life
\p
\v 11 Sha'ul sent¦135269 messengers¦135271 to watch¦135276 David's house¦135274 to \add ≈kill¦135277\add* him in the morning¦135278, but his wife Mikal told \add *him\add*, “If you don't¦135286 \add do something to\add* save your life¦135290 tonight, you'll be dead by tomorrow¦135292.”\x + \xo 19:11: \xt Psa 59 header.\x*
\v 12 \add ≈So¦135296\add* Mikal lowered¦135296 David out through¦135301 the window¦135302, and he was able to slip out and take off.
\v 13 Then¦135307 \add *she\add* took¦135307 a household idol¦135311 and put it in the bed, putting a goats' hair quilt¦135317 \add ≈where the head should be\add* and covering¦135321 it with the \add bed-\add*clothes.
\v 14 \add ≈When\add* Sha'ul sent¦135325 messengers¦135327 to \add ≈arrest\add* David, she \add ≈told\add* \add <them\add*, “He's sick¦135333.”
\v 15 Sha'ul sent¦135337 the messengers¦135341 \add back\add*, \add ≈telling\add* \add <them\add*, “Bring him up to me \add ≈bed and all so I can kill¦135351 him\add*.”
\v 16 \add ≈But¦135353\add* when the messengers¦135354 \add ≈returned\add*, look, it was a household idol¦135356 in the bed with a goats' hair quilt¦135360 as its¦135362 head.
\v 17 Sha'ul \add had Mikal brought in and\add* \add ≈questioned\add*, “Why did you deceive¦135371 me like that and sent my enemy¦135375 off, so that he slipped away?”
\p “He \add ≈told me that he'd kill¦135388 me\add*,” Michal \add ≈answered\add* Saul, “\add ≈if I didn't help him escape¦135376\add*.”
\rem /s1 David Joins Samuel in Ramah
\p
\v 18 \add After\add* David had slipped away, he went to Shemuel in Ramah and told him everything that Sha'ul had done to him, then \add ≈the two of them\add* went and stayed in Nayot.
\v 19 \add ≈But¦135416\add* Sha'ul was told that David was in Nayot \add ≈near\add* Ramah,
\v 20 \add ≈so\add* \add *he\add* sent¦135425 messengers to \add ≈capture\add* David. \add ≈When\add* they saw¦135432 a group of prophets prophesying and Shemuel standing¦135439 \add ≈as head\add* over them, God's spirit¦135447 came onto Sha'ul's messengers and they also prophesied.
\v 21 They told Sha'ul and he sent more messengers and they also prophesied. \add *He\add* sent messengers a third¦135467 time, and they \add started\add* prophesying as well.
\v 22 \add ≈Finally\add* Sha'ul \add himself\add* \add ≈headed towards\add* Ramah and got as far as the large \add water\add* cistern¦135481 in Seku. He asked¦135485 \add ≈around about\add* Shemuel and David, and \add ≈was told that\add* they were in Nayot \add ≈near\add* Ramah.
\v 23 \add ≈So¦135496\add* he went¦135515 to Nayot, and God's spirit¦135508 came on him as well. As he \add ≈walked\add*, he \add kept\add* prophesying¦135512 until¦135513 he entered Nayot.
\v 24 He took off his \add outer\add* clothes¦135524 and prophesied \add ≈in front¦135529\add* of Shemuel. He lay \add ≈undressed\add* all that day¦135535 and all night¦135539, so \add that's why\add* people¦135543 ask, “Is Sha'ul a prophet as well?”\x + \xo 19:24: \xt 1Sam 10:11-12.\x*
\c 20
\s1 Yonatan helps David
\rem /s1 The Friendship of David and Jonathan; Jonathan Helps David
\p
\v 1 Then David fled from Nayot \add ≈near\add* Ramah and went¦135554 to Yonatan and \add ≈asked\add*, “What have I done? What did I do wrong? What sin¦135566 \add ≈has made your father so angry\add* that he \add ≈wants to take\add* my life¦135573?”
\p
\v 2 “Far from it,” Yonatan \add ≈responded\add*. “You won't die. Listen, my father doesn't do \add ≈anything, big or small¦135590, without telling me\add*. \add ≈So¦135575\add* why would my father hide this from me \add if it was his plan\add*? \add No,\add* \add ≈you're wrong\add*.”
\p
\v 3 “For sure, your father knows¦135612 that \add ≈you've taken a liking to me\add*,” said David, “and he \add ≈would have decided not to tell you so you wouldn't be upset\add*.” Then¦135607 David made an oath again¦135608, “Indeed, as Yahweh is alive, and as your soul¦135634 is alive, death¦135639 \add ≈is definitely only a step away from me\add*.”
\p
\v 4 “I'll do anything for you—whatever¦135646 you say¦135648,” Yonatan \add ≈confirmed\add*.
\p
\v 5 “Listen, the new moon \add celebration\add* is tomorrow, and \add ≈I'll definitely be expected to\add* sit with the king to eat,” David told \add *him\add*. “\add ≈But\add* you \add should\add* let me go, and I'll hide myself in the countryside until the third evening.\x + \xo 20:5: \xt Num 28:11.\x*
\v 6 If your father misses me, then tell \add <him\add*, ‘David \add ≈fervently requested me to let him go to his home in\add* Bethlehem, to \add ≈join his clan for their yearly\add* sacrifice.’
\v 7 If \add @your father\add* says, ‘That's fine,’ then your servant \add ≈can relax\add*. \add ≈But if he gets really angry\add*, \add ≈you'll know that he's planning\add* evil.
\v 8 \add If that's the case,\add* \add ≈it'll be up to you to do what's right with your servant in terms of our agreement before\add* Yahweh. If \add ≈I've been disloyal to the king,\add* kill me yourself—\add ≈no need to drag me to him\add*.
\p
\v 9 “\add ≈Don't even think of it\add*,” Yonatan \add ≈responded\add*. “If I find out that my father \add ≈has decided to harm\add* you, I'll \add ≈certainly\add* tell you.”
\p
\v 10 “If your father \add ≈does have a cruel plan\add*, who'll tell me?” David \add ≈asked\add* Yonatan.
\p
\v 11 “Come \add ≈with me\add* out to the countryside.” Yonatan \add ≈replied\add*. 
